WEBVTT

cue-1
00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.840
Hi, and welcome to this video about
choosing the right AI architecture.

cue-2
00:00:07.120 --> 00:00:12.060
As an AI product manager, selecting the
right architecture is a critical step in

cue-3
00:00:12.060 --> 00:00:16.020
building an AI application. You will often
need to choose between three main

cue-4
00:00:16.020 --> 00:00:16.590
approaches:

cue-5
00:00:17.220 --> 00:00:18.900
retrieval-augmented generation,

cue-6
00:00:19.580 --> 00:00:20.130
fine-tuning,

cue-7
00:00:20.780 --> 00:00:24.740
and agentic workflows. This decision
matters because it directly affects

cue-8
00:00:24.740 --> 00:00:29.640
development cost, system latency, and the
overall user experience. Since every

cue-9
00:00:29.640 --> 00:00:33.440
product has different constraints, your
goal is to evaluate these trade-offs and

cue-10
00:00:33.440 --> 00:00:37.020
choose the approach that best aligns with
your needs. Choosing the wrong

cue-11
00:00:37.020 --> 00:00:40.960
architecture can lead to high costs or a
system that fails to meet user

cue-12
00:00:40.960 --> 00:00:41.860
expectations.

cue-13
00:00:43.940 --> 00:00:47.320
At a high level, the difference between
these approaches comes down to three

cue-14
00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:51.900
things: where knowledge comes from, how
reasoning happens, and how much control

cue-15
00:00:51.900 --> 00:00:53.560
you have over the system's behavior.

cue-16
00:00:54.260 --> 00:00:55.960
A simple way to remember them is this:

cue-17
00:00:56.640 --> 00:01:01.520
RAG looks it up, fine-tuning memorizes it,
and agentic workflows think through it.

cue-18
00:01:03.740 --> 00:01:06.860
Let's start with retrieval-augmented
generation, or RAG.

cue-19
00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:12.920
With RAG, the model retrieves information
from an external source, such as documents

cue-20
00:01:12.920 --> 00:01:17.640
or a knowledge base, and then uses that
information to generate a response. You

cue-21
00:01:17.640 --> 00:01:20.400
can think of it as search combined with AI
explanation.

cue-22
00:01:21.060 --> 00:01:23.670
RAG is often attractive because it is
faster to build,

cue-23
00:01:24.340 --> 00:01:29.300
easier to update, and lower cost than
other approaches. If your content changes

cue-24
00:01:29.300 --> 00:01:33.700
frequently, you can update the knowledge
source without retraining the model. This

cue-25
00:01:33.700 --> 00:01:37.780
makes RAG a strong fit for systems that
rely on up-to-date or domain-specific

cue-26
00:01:37.780 --> 00:01:38.420
information.

cue-27
00:01:40.600 --> 00:01:42.620
However, RAG also has limitations.

cue-28
00:01:43.400 --> 00:01:47.500
Its performance depends heavily on the
quality of retrieval. If the wrong

cue-29
00:01:47.500 --> 00:01:52.039
information is retrieved or if the task
requires deeper reasoning, the response

cue-30
00:01:52.040 --> 00:01:54.000
may be shallow or inconsistent.

cue-31
00:01:54.680 --> 00:01:59.180
As a result, RAG works best for FAQ
systems, knowledge-based chatbots, or

cue-32
00:01:59.180 --> 00:02:02.000
assistants that primarily reference
external content.

cue-33
00:02:04.200 --> 00:02:05.120
Next is fine-tuning.

cue-34
00:02:05.780 --> 00:02:10.359
Fine-tuning improves the model itself by
training it on a specific data set.

cue-35
00:02:10.360 --> 00:02:14.240
Instead of retrieving information each
time, the model learns patterns directly

cue-36
00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:18.180
from examples. In simple terms,
fine-tuning teaches the model how to

cue-37
00:02:18.180 --> 00:02:18.600
respond.

cue-38
00:02:19.230 --> 00:02:22.980
This approach is useful when you need
consistent tone, stronger domain

cue-39
00:02:22.980 --> 00:02:28.040
expertise, or tighter control over
outputs. For example, if you want an AI

cue-40
00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:31.980
tutor to consistently follow a specific
teaching style, fine-tuning may be more

cue-41
00:02:31.980 --> 00:02:33.480
effective than RAG alone.

cue-42
00:02:35.440 --> 00:02:40.560
However, fine-tuning requires high-quality
label data, more development effort, and

cue-43
00:02:40.560 --> 00:02:45.400
higher upfront cost. It is also less
flexible when requirements change.

cue-44
00:02:45.400 --> 00:02:50.220
Fine-tuning is best suited for specialized
products, branded assistants, or systems

cue-45
00:02:50.220 --> 00:02:51.840
that require consistent behavior.

cue-46
00:02:54.120 --> 00:02:58.800
Finally, there are agentic workflows. With
agentic workflows, the system breaks

cue-47
00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:04.420
tasks into multiple steps. It can plan,
use tools, evaluate intermediate results,

cue-48
00:03:04.420 --> 00:03:08.080
revise its output, and then produce a
final answer.

cue-49
00:03:08.120 --> 00:03:12.520
Instead of responding all at once, it
works through a structured process. This

cue-50
00:03:12.520 --> 00:03:17.310
makes agentic workflows especially
powerful for complex multi-step tasks that

cue-51
00:03:17.310 --> 00:03:21.740
require deeper reasoning and greater
control. For example, in a tutoring

cue-52
00:03:21.740 --> 00:03:25.640
system, an agent can guide a student step
by step rather than jumping straight to

cue-53
00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:26.120
the answer.

cue-54
00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:31.400
The trade-off is that agentic workflows
are slower, more complex to build, and

cue-55
00:03:31.400 --> 00:03:32.380
more expensive to run.

cue-56
00:03:34.600 --> 00:03:35.460
So how do you decide?

cue-57
00:03:36.100 --> 00:03:40.120
In practice, there is no single best
approach. In many cases, you may even

cue-58
00:03:40.120 --> 00:03:44.820
combine methods. For example, you might
use fine-tuning to control tone while

cue-59
00:03:44.820 --> 00:03:48.840
using RAG to provide up-to-date
information or use an agentic workflow to

cue-60
00:03:48.840 --> 00:03:52.760
manage more complex reasoning on top of
retrieval. Understanding how these

cue-61
00:03:52.760 --> 00:03:56.359
approaches can work together allows you to
build more flexible and effective

cue-62
00:03:56.360 --> 00:04:01.840
systems. But even with these options,
making the right decision can be

cue-63
00:04:01.840 --> 00:04:06.880
challenging. When you're balancing cost,
speed, and quality, it's easy to rely on

cue-64
00:04:06.880 --> 00:04:09.049
intuition or incomplete information.

cue-65
00:04:09.940 --> 00:04:12.990
To make this process more systematic, we
use the EVAL framework.

cue-66
00:04:13.840 --> 00:04:18.060
The EVAL framework provides a structured
way to evaluate these trade-offs and make

cue-67
00:04:18.060 --> 00:04:22.320
decisions based on data instead of
intuition. There are five stages in the

cue-68
00:04:22.320 --> 00:04:23.100
EVAL framework.

cue-69
00:04:25.240 --> 00:04:26.160
Stage one, setup,

cue-70
00:04:26.840 --> 00:04:30.660
is where you define what success looks
like by creating a clear rubric for the

cue-71
00:04:30.660 --> 00:04:35.220
LLM judge and a test data set for the AI
system, so the system's outputs can be

cue-72
00:04:35.220 --> 00:04:38.170
evaluated by the LLM consistently and
automatically.

cue-73
00:04:40.420 --> 00:04:45.020
Stage two, audit, is where human
evaluators review and verify the LLM's

cue-74
00:04:45.020 --> 00:04:49.160
judgments to make sure the evaluation is
accurate and aligned with your goals.

cue-75
00:04:51.360 --> 00:04:56.000
Stage three, diagnose, is where you
analyze the evaluation results from LLM

cue-76
00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.600
Judge based on the rubric and data set to
identify the root cause of the system's

cue-77
00:05:00.600 --> 00:05:03.640
failures rather than just observing
surface-level issues.

cue-78
00:05:05.820 --> 00:05:10.800
Stage four, decide, is where you select
the best solution based on your diagnosis

cue-79
00:05:10.800 --> 00:05:14.200
while balancing important trade-offs like
quality, speed, and cost.

cue-80
00:05:16.380 --> 00:05:21.000
Stage five, optimize, is where you make
the solution workable at scale by

cue-81
00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:24.500
improving its cost structure and
evaluating whether it is sustainable in

cue-82
00:05:24.500 --> 00:05:25.010
production.

cue-83
00:05:26.630 --> 00:05:30.980
Together, these five stages guide you
through a complete structured process for

cue-84
00:05:30.980 --> 00:05:33.910
improving AI systems using data instead of
guesswork.

cue-85
00:05:34.580 --> 00:05:35.290
Now, let's begin.
